$AMD CEO Lisa Su saying we‚Äôre ‚Äúat the beginning of AI‚Äù matters because it shows the demand they‚Äôre seeing isn‚Äôt slowing.

If customers are only now feeling real productivity gains then the AI buildout is just entering the phase where companies lock in larger, longer commitments.

$NVDA is tightening its Rubin supply chain by shifting suppliers to full L10 builds while Nvidia handles the final rack stage. 

Rubin becomes Nvidia‚Äôs first fully standardized end-to-end AI system where cooling, networking, power & integration all run through a single playbook.

MY 5 BIGGEST TAKEAWAYS FROM $AMD ANALYST DAY 

1. The pivot is official that AMD it‚Äôs building a platform with a goal is to sell full AI infrastructure: silicon, interconnect, software & racks that hyperscalers can deploy at scale. It‚Äôs chasing $NVDA vertical model but through an open ecosystem.

2. Data center is the company with Lisa guiding for ~35% CAGR, 57% gross margins & >$20 EPS by 2030. That requires DC biz to grow from ~$16B today to near $100B within five years which is a 6x run that only works if MI450 + Helios hit ramp targets & hyperscaler orders stack fast.

3. GPU is the upside but ROCm is the gatekeeper. The MI450 & yearly GPU cadence will define whether AMD becomes a real platform or stays a second source. Success hinges on ROCm feeling as stable and integrated as CUDA but partnerships with $META, $ORCL & OpenAI are the first real signs of ecosystem lift.

4. CPUs fund the fight with the server share near 40% gives AMD the profit engine it needs. As AI inference workloads push compute back toward CPUs, crossing 50% share does actually look realistic & that stable cash flow supports GPU & software expansion without breaking margins.

5. Michael Burry is wrong.

Macro guys keep complaining about $MSFT, $AMZN, $META & $GOOGL pouring billions into GPUs & yelling ‚Äúbubble‚Äù because humans are terrible at recognizing exponential change while it‚Äôs happening.

What looks like reckless CapEx is just hyperscalers buying future margin. These companies print tens of billions in free cash flow every quarter so they can afford to reinvest.

Do you really want them to be short-sighted and just chase buybacks or do you want them to build the infrastructure that will power intelligence for the next decade?

Every GPU cluster deployed today lowers the cost of inference tomorrow. They‚Äôre not paying for the present but they‚Äôre prepaying for the decade of gross margin that comes once this infrastructure is fully utilized.

Spend aggressively & build the backbone then let operating leverage do the rest.

Our three favorite AI utility names:

‚Ä¢ $NBIS builds across the software + developer layer
‚Ä¢ $IREN builds down into power + compute
‚Ä¢ $CIFR rents out the physical layer through long-term leases
